WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.856
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:05.856 --> 00:00:09.652
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:09.652 --> 00:00:11.610
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Thank
you for joining us today.

00:00:11.610 --> 00:00:15.200
I am also a UW alum, so
I'm excited to be back

00:00:15.200 --> 00:00:16.862
in that territory.

00:00:16.862 --> 00:00:19.070
DAVID LEVIN: So when I first
saw this book, "Creating

00:00:19.070 --> 00:00:20.945
Compassionate Kids,
Essential Conversations,"

00:00:20.945 --> 00:00:23.270
my impression was that
it's a book for parents

00:00:23.270 --> 00:00:24.470
with young children.

00:00:24.470 --> 00:00:26.039
Is that the audience?

00:00:26.039 --> 00:00:27.830
What's your intended
audience for the book?

00:00:27.830 --> 00:00:30.020
SHAUNA TOMINEY: So my intended
audience is, like you said,

00:00:30.020 --> 00:00:30.650
parents.

00:00:30.650 --> 00:00:32.720
But I define parents
very broadly.

00:00:32.720 --> 00:00:35.240
There are a lot of people who
are serving a parenting role

00:00:35.240 --> 00:00:36.570
in the lives of young children.

00:00:36.570 --> 00:00:39.020
We have parents who
are biological parents,

00:00:39.020 --> 00:00:42.560
foster parents, step-parents,
grandparents, aunts and uncles.

00:00:42.560 --> 00:00:45.050
Sometimes its neighbors,
community members,

00:00:45.050 --> 00:00:47.000
early childhood teachers
or other caregivers,

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:50.620
really anybody with young
children in their lives.

00:00:50.620 --> 00:00:53.120
DAVID LEVIN: And there's some
emphasis on young children

00:00:53.120 --> 00:00:57.800
and kids, but what about
teenagers and older kids?

00:00:57.800 --> 00:00:59.970
Does it apply to them at all?

00:00:59.970 --> 00:01:03.050
SHAUNA TOMINEY: I think that a
lot of the foundation of what

00:01:03.050 --> 00:01:06.470
we do with our young
children forms the foundation

00:01:06.470 --> 00:01:08.930
for those relationships
that we have with older kids

00:01:08.930 --> 00:01:10.010
and with teens.

00:01:10.010 --> 00:01:12.909
And so often, the same
things that we struggle

00:01:12.909 --> 00:01:14.450
with our younger
children-- how do we

00:01:14.450 --> 00:01:16.940
have conversations
about tough topics?

00:01:16.940 --> 00:01:19.529
How do we help them manage
their tough emotions?

00:01:19.529 --> 00:01:22.070
This is something that doesn't
go away as children get older.

00:01:22.070 --> 00:01:24.470
So there are some things
in the book that are very

00:01:24.470 --> 00:01:25.850
specific to young children--

00:01:25.850 --> 00:01:29.060
I make storybook recommendations
for how to talk about some

00:01:29.060 --> 00:01:30.380
of these topics--

00:01:30.380 --> 00:01:32.442
that really are targeted
for those picture

00:01:32.442 --> 00:01:33.650
books and those younger ages.

00:01:33.650 --> 00:01:37.010
But a lot of the messages
lay that foundation

00:01:37.010 --> 00:01:39.080
that should be true
throughout childhood

00:01:39.080 --> 00:01:41.456
and into the teen years.

00:01:41.456 --> 00:01:44.016
DAVID LEVIN: One other broad
question about the book.

00:01:44.016 --> 00:01:45.890
Now there have been a
lot of parenting books.

00:01:45.890 --> 00:01:48.350
And some of them give
perhaps questionable

00:01:48.350 --> 00:01:52.840
advice that sometimes doesn't
seem so good in retrospect.

00:01:52.840 --> 00:01:55.737
How do we know we can
trust your book here?

00:01:55.737 --> 00:01:56.571
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:56.571 --> 00:01:58.490
SHAUNA TOMINEY: That's
a great question,

00:01:58.490 --> 00:02:00.740
and an important question
to ask, especially

00:02:00.740 --> 00:02:04.280
because we know how easy
it is to get information.

00:02:04.280 --> 00:02:06.560
And how many of you are parents?

00:02:06.560 --> 00:02:08.300
Can I ask?

00:02:08.300 --> 00:02:11.030
OK, so the vast
majority in the room.

00:02:11.030 --> 00:02:13.610
And whether you're a parent
now or plan to be a parent,

00:02:13.610 --> 00:02:15.590
or have a young
child in your life

00:02:15.590 --> 00:02:17.870
or an older child in
your life in another way,

00:02:17.870 --> 00:02:20.060
we are inundated
with information

00:02:20.060 --> 00:02:23.450
on what it means to be a parent,
what parenting looks like, what

00:02:23.450 --> 00:02:25.490
parenting should look like.

00:02:25.490 --> 00:02:30.170
And sometimes that information
is very, very conflicting.

00:02:30.170 --> 00:02:33.404
I teach a parenting class
at Oregon State University.

00:02:33.404 --> 00:02:34.820
And one of the
activities we do is

00:02:34.820 --> 00:02:37.790
we pick topics like
immunizations or some

00:02:37.790 --> 00:02:39.680
of these other
challenging topics

00:02:39.680 --> 00:02:43.340
that might have conflicting
viewpoints represented

00:02:43.340 --> 00:02:44.900
on the internet or
in other sources,

00:02:44.900 --> 00:02:48.649
and look at where do you
find that information.

00:02:48.649 --> 00:02:50.690
And what you find is that
you'll find information

00:02:50.690 --> 00:02:52.529
on all sides of an argument.

00:02:52.529 --> 00:02:55.070
And so that's a great question
to ask about a parenting book.

00:02:55.070 --> 00:02:56.111
Because the same is true.

00:02:56.111 --> 00:02:58.160
There are a lot of
parenting books out.

00:02:58.160 --> 00:03:02.030
And many of them offer
potentially conflicting advice

00:03:02.030 --> 00:03:05.120
or sometimes advice that's not
really grounded in research.

00:03:05.120 --> 00:03:09.260
So one of the
beliefs that I have

00:03:09.260 --> 00:03:11.600
is that you should be very
transparent about where

00:03:11.600 --> 00:03:13.220
your information comes from.

00:03:13.220 --> 00:03:16.070
And so I try to be really
open in the book itself

00:03:16.070 --> 00:03:18.500
about both my personal
experiences, which are

00:03:18.500 --> 00:03:20.300
blended into what I talk about.

00:03:20.300 --> 00:03:22.500
I've been an early
childhood educator.

00:03:22.500 --> 00:03:25.130
I've been a parenting educator,
and trained in those best

00:03:25.130 --> 00:03:27.500
practices for how
we teach children

00:03:27.500 --> 00:03:30.320
about emotions, how
we teach them to talk

00:03:30.320 --> 00:03:31.710
about these tough topics.

00:03:31.710 --> 00:03:34.700
And quite frankly,
there's a lot that we

00:03:34.700 --> 00:03:38.310
know in child development
about how children grow,

00:03:38.310 --> 00:03:39.950
develop, and thrive.

00:03:39.950 --> 00:03:44.420
But as parents, it's not so easy
to take that information that's

00:03:44.420 --> 00:03:47.510
in the textbooks
that are available

00:03:47.510 --> 00:03:49.490
and actually turn that
into parenting practices

00:03:49.490 --> 00:03:50.990
and deal with the
challenges that we

00:03:50.990 --> 00:03:53.730
might have every day
with our young children.

00:03:53.730 --> 00:03:58.280
And so in coming to this,
having been in the field,

00:03:58.280 --> 00:04:00.560
having heard thousands
of conversations

00:04:00.560 --> 00:04:03.890
with children and parents
around the country,

00:04:03.890 --> 00:04:05.900
and seen what parents
really struggle with,

00:04:05.900 --> 00:04:08.490
what I've tried to do is take
the research we know about--

00:04:08.490 --> 00:04:11.030
OK, what is it that
helps children thrive--

00:04:11.030 --> 00:04:12.980
and put it into
practice, but also

00:04:12.980 --> 00:04:14.640
blend that with those
personal stories.

00:04:14.640 --> 00:04:16.098
So I try to be as
clear as possible

00:04:16.098 --> 00:04:18.950
of where that's happening so
that the reader has a chance

00:04:18.950 --> 00:04:20.920
to take that
information in yourself.

00:04:20.920 --> 00:04:24.110
Now in this book, we
go through and talk

00:04:24.110 --> 00:04:26.510
about different examples of
challenging conversations

00:04:26.510 --> 00:04:28.040
to have with young children.

00:04:28.040 --> 00:04:29.990
And I'll never say
there's one right way

00:04:29.990 --> 00:04:32.620
to talk about this topic.

00:04:32.620 --> 00:04:34.130
Here are some examples.

00:04:34.130 --> 00:04:35.950
Here's what we know in research.

00:04:35.950 --> 00:04:38.440
And let's add this to
your parenting toolbox

00:04:38.440 --> 00:04:39.885
so you can make a choice.

00:04:39.885 --> 00:04:41.890
DAVID LEVIN: And I really like
how after the conversations,

00:04:41.890 --> 00:04:43.030
you go through and
you go, these are

00:04:43.030 --> 00:04:45.400
the key things that we're trying
to do in this conversation.

00:04:45.400 --> 00:04:45.715
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Yeah.

00:04:45.715 --> 00:04:47.798
DAVID LEVIN: So you can
take away that and kind of

00:04:47.798 --> 00:04:49.735
adapt the conversation
to your style somewhat.

00:04:49.735 --> 00:04:50.860
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Absolutely.

00:04:50.860 --> 00:04:54.170
DAVID LEVIN: And I think you did
a great job of explaining it.

00:04:54.170 --> 00:04:56.680
And I know in the about
section about you,

00:04:56.680 --> 00:04:59.860
it says that you blend practical
experience with research

00:04:59.860 --> 00:05:01.510
to develop and
test programs aimed

00:05:01.510 --> 00:05:04.870
at promoting social emotional
skills for children and adults.

00:05:04.870 --> 00:05:06.594
And I felt like that
kind of captured

00:05:06.594 --> 00:05:09.010
a little bit of what you were
doing in the book, where you

00:05:09.010 --> 00:05:10.720
kind of talk about some
of the practical side,

00:05:10.720 --> 00:05:13.220
and you mentioned the references
to various bits of research

00:05:13.220 --> 00:05:15.340
throughout.

00:05:15.340 --> 00:05:17.680
One of the first things you
cover in the book was you

00:05:17.680 --> 00:05:20.312
said there's the most
important conversation

00:05:20.312 --> 00:05:21.520
you can have with your child.

00:05:21.520 --> 00:05:22.690
What is that?

00:05:22.690 --> 00:05:25.690
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Well, one of
the most important conversations

00:05:25.690 --> 00:05:29.110
you can really have is about
loving and accepting your child

00:05:29.110 --> 00:05:30.560
for who they are.

00:05:30.560 --> 00:05:33.120
That's absolutely foundational
to building trust,

00:05:33.120 --> 00:05:35.410
to let your child know that
you're not always going

00:05:35.410 --> 00:05:37.120
to love everything they do.

00:05:37.120 --> 00:05:39.850
You're not always going
to be behind every choice

00:05:39.850 --> 00:05:41.210
that they make.

00:05:41.210 --> 00:05:44.560
But you'll always be there
for them as a person.

00:05:44.560 --> 00:05:47.560
And that's moving
toward that acceptance

00:05:47.560 --> 00:05:51.620
of who they are without shaming
them for being that person.

00:05:51.620 --> 00:05:54.580
So really looking at how do we
love and accept our children

00:05:54.580 --> 00:05:57.310
for who they are, and help
them understand not only

00:05:57.310 --> 00:05:59.950
who they are now, but
who they will grow into

00:05:59.950 --> 00:06:02.395
and who they will
become as we also

00:06:02.395 --> 00:06:04.790
then help guide them through
some of these challenges.

00:06:04.790 --> 00:06:07.570
Because we don't always
like what our children do.

00:06:07.570 --> 00:06:10.657
We don't always like or support
the decisions they make.

00:06:10.657 --> 00:06:12.490
But that doesn't mean
that we won't be there

00:06:12.490 --> 00:06:16.030
for them to come back to us, and
feel like they have that trust

00:06:16.030 --> 00:06:18.140
to know that we'll be
there, no matter what.

00:06:18.140 --> 00:06:18.940
DAVID LEVIN: Yeah.

00:06:18.940 --> 00:06:21.344
And I hear you mentioning
trust a lot right now.

00:06:21.344 --> 00:06:23.260
And I feel like that's
a theme that you hit on

00:06:23.260 --> 00:06:24.180
throughout the book.

00:06:24.180 --> 00:06:27.620
Why is that so important,
the trust with your child

00:06:27.620 --> 00:06:28.465
and so on?

00:06:28.465 --> 00:06:30.370
SHAUNA TOMINEY:
Well, as I mentioned,

00:06:30.370 --> 00:06:34.450
having that trust is so
foundational to relationships

00:06:34.450 --> 00:06:36.520
in early childhood and beyond.

00:06:36.520 --> 00:06:38.126
When children feel
like they can trust

00:06:38.126 --> 00:06:40.000
the parents and the
caregivers in their lives

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:43.300
to be there for them, they're
more likely to turn to them

00:06:43.300 --> 00:06:45.070
when challenges come up.

00:06:45.070 --> 00:06:46.790
They want to be like them.

00:06:46.790 --> 00:06:48.970
They want to learn from them.

00:06:48.970 --> 00:06:52.610
It's easier to teach and
guide them along the way.

00:06:52.610 --> 00:06:55.480
We also know that when
children experience stress--

00:06:55.480 --> 00:06:56.620
which we all do.

00:06:56.620 --> 00:06:58.000
We all experience stress.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:00.010
And so often as
a parent, we want

00:07:00.010 --> 00:07:02.230
to shield our child from stress.

00:07:02.230 --> 00:07:05.270
We want to keep them
kids as long as possible.

00:07:05.270 --> 00:07:07.450
And we want to help them
avoid stressful situations.

00:07:07.450 --> 00:07:10.819
But the reality is they're
going to experience stress.

00:07:10.819 --> 00:07:12.610
And they're going to
experience challenges.

00:07:12.610 --> 00:07:17.140
And knowing that we will be
there to help them through that

00:07:17.140 --> 00:07:19.367
can have serious implications.

00:07:19.367 --> 00:07:20.950
We're seeing in
research that children

00:07:20.950 --> 00:07:24.100
who have trusting relationships
with adults in their lives

00:07:24.100 --> 00:07:26.470
who can help them through
stress can actually

00:07:26.470 --> 00:07:30.672
minimize the impact of
that stress long term.

00:07:30.672 --> 00:07:32.740
DAVID LEVIN: And how
do the conversations

00:07:32.740 --> 00:07:35.350
that we have with our kids
help to build that trust?

00:07:35.350 --> 00:07:38.890
What types of things
do we do, or even

00:07:38.890 --> 00:07:40.314
not do or maybe undermine it?

00:07:40.314 --> 00:07:41.230
You can touch on both.

00:07:41.230 --> 00:07:42.882
SHAUNA TOMINEY:
Yeah, absolutely.

00:07:42.882 --> 00:07:44.590
I think one of the
biggest things we hear

00:07:44.590 --> 00:07:47.820
is that children--

00:07:47.820 --> 00:07:50.560
as I mentioned, as
parents, we often

00:07:50.560 --> 00:07:53.465
want to protect our
children from stress.

00:07:53.465 --> 00:07:55.090
And we want to protect
them from things

00:07:55.090 --> 00:07:57.100
that we're worried
they're not ready for yet.

00:07:57.100 --> 00:08:00.070
There's so much out
there in the world

00:08:00.070 --> 00:08:01.570
that our children
are going to face.

00:08:01.570 --> 00:08:02.986
There are so many
things that they

00:08:02.986 --> 00:08:05.140
might see, that
they might overhear,

00:08:05.140 --> 00:08:07.960
that they might become
exposed to on the internet,

00:08:07.960 --> 00:08:09.940
at school, on the
news, whether or not

00:08:09.940 --> 00:08:12.220
we want them to
be exposed to it,

00:08:12.220 --> 00:08:14.320
that oftentimes, when our
very young children come

00:08:14.320 --> 00:08:15.820
to us with these
questions of things

00:08:15.820 --> 00:08:19.210
that they're seeing or
hearing, we turn to them

00:08:19.210 --> 00:08:22.590
and say, well, let's talk
about that when you're older.

00:08:22.590 --> 00:08:28.150
Or let's wait and talk
about that another time.

00:08:28.150 --> 00:08:31.240
And what we mean is,
I want to protect you.

00:08:31.240 --> 00:08:33.890
I want you to be a child
as long as possible.

00:08:33.890 --> 00:08:36.880
I don't want you to have
to worry about that now.

00:08:36.880 --> 00:08:40.150
What our children
might hear is, I can't

00:08:40.150 --> 00:08:42.350
come to you to talk about this.

00:08:42.350 --> 00:08:44.590
And that's something that
we really want to avoid,

00:08:44.590 --> 00:08:47.530
is not giving our
child that message

00:08:47.530 --> 00:08:49.357
without meaning
to that we're not

00:08:49.357 --> 00:08:51.190
going to be the ones
who are there to answer

00:08:51.190 --> 00:08:52.382
those questions for them.

00:08:52.382 --> 00:08:54.340
DAVID LEVIN: Yeah, and
I think related to that,

00:08:54.340 --> 00:08:56.020
you have a whole
chapter in here devoted

00:08:56.020 --> 00:09:00.920
to heavy topics like death
and divorce and so on.

00:09:00.920 --> 00:09:03.700
And yet those related for
kids and young children.

00:09:03.700 --> 00:09:06.077
Is this something that we can
wait to talk to them about?

00:09:06.077 --> 00:09:07.910
I think you were talking
about some already.

00:09:07.910 --> 00:09:09.207
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Yeah.

00:09:09.207 --> 00:09:09.790
You know what?

00:09:09.790 --> 00:09:13.030
It really depends on our
child, the age of our child,

00:09:13.030 --> 00:09:15.610
who our child is, and
what we experience.

00:09:15.610 --> 00:09:18.400
So often we talk to our
child about what we know.

00:09:18.400 --> 00:09:21.760
We talk to them about what it
is we are experiencing, what it

00:09:21.760 --> 00:09:23.470
is we know that they're seeing.

00:09:23.470 --> 00:09:27.310
And if you don't mind me
stepping back a moment,

00:09:27.310 --> 00:09:30.790
just in setting this up--

00:09:30.790 --> 00:09:34.080
when I have had the
opportunity to really

00:09:34.080 --> 00:09:36.480
live in different
places in the country

00:09:36.480 --> 00:09:39.090
and to hear the different
kinds of conversations

00:09:39.090 --> 00:09:42.430
that children and adults
have in different settings.

00:09:42.430 --> 00:09:44.220
And one of the
things that I've seen

00:09:44.220 --> 00:09:48.330
is that most parents talk
to children about how much

00:09:48.330 --> 00:09:51.600
they love them, their hopes
and their dreams for them,

00:09:51.600 --> 00:09:54.600
what they want for them.

00:09:54.600 --> 00:09:56.550
But there are also
a lot of differences

00:09:56.550 --> 00:09:59.370
in the kinds of conversations
that parents and children have,

00:09:59.370 --> 00:10:01.560
and that varies by context.

00:10:01.560 --> 00:10:05.580
And there are some
children who never

00:10:05.580 --> 00:10:07.710
grow up talking
about death, or never

00:10:07.710 --> 00:10:09.497
grow up talking about stress.

00:10:09.497 --> 00:10:11.580
But on the flip side, there
are other families who

00:10:11.580 --> 00:10:13.485
talk about that all the time.

00:10:13.485 --> 00:10:15.360
So when I was working
with military families,

00:10:15.360 --> 00:10:17.820
for example, those
families were talking

00:10:17.820 --> 00:10:20.010
about the stress
of being deployed

00:10:20.010 --> 00:10:23.560
or separated from a loved one
from for a long period of time,

00:10:23.560 --> 00:10:26.400
and the possible death
or the reality of having

00:10:26.400 --> 00:10:30.210
a death in the
family as a result.

00:10:30.210 --> 00:10:34.770
When I was working in
inner city urban areas,

00:10:34.770 --> 00:10:38.850
there were families there who
talked every day about how

00:10:38.850 --> 00:10:41.100
the impact of the color
of their child's skin

00:10:41.100 --> 00:10:43.740
would affect how they
were being looked at,

00:10:43.740 --> 00:10:46.260
the opportunities that
they had, or the reason

00:10:46.260 --> 00:10:48.240
that people would
cross the street

00:10:48.240 --> 00:10:50.610
to avoid standing next to them.

00:10:50.610 --> 00:10:52.830
And yet these were the
kinds of conversations

00:10:52.830 --> 00:10:55.470
that other families
weren't having.

00:10:55.470 --> 00:10:58.560
And often, when I think
about this, and whether

00:10:58.560 --> 00:11:01.200
or not we should tackle some of
these tough conversations, what

00:11:01.200 --> 00:11:04.260
I'm reminded of is that
some of these topics

00:11:04.260 --> 00:11:08.580
define a young child's
life every single day.

00:11:08.580 --> 00:11:10.890
There are parents who
don't have a choice, who

00:11:10.890 --> 00:11:12.930
have to tackle
these tough topics

00:11:12.930 --> 00:11:15.000
because they define
their child's life,

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:17.400
how their child is looked
at, the opportunities

00:11:17.400 --> 00:11:18.930
that their child has.

00:11:18.930 --> 00:11:20.790
And it was having
that experience

00:11:20.790 --> 00:11:23.190
to see all of these
different experiences

00:11:23.190 --> 00:11:25.680
that children and families had
that really got me thinking

00:11:25.680 --> 00:11:28.290
about this book, and to
think about, how do I

00:11:28.290 --> 00:11:32.820
as a parent use this opportunity
that I've had to see and peer

00:11:32.820 --> 00:11:35.760
into the lives of all of
these children and families,

00:11:35.760 --> 00:11:38.550
and to think about for my own
child and then the children

00:11:38.550 --> 00:11:42.300
that I work with, how do we
help them be more compassionate?

00:11:42.300 --> 00:11:44.430
How do we help them
get those skills

00:11:44.430 --> 00:11:47.702
to prepare for what they
might face in their lives,

00:11:47.702 --> 00:11:49.410
but also to be more
understanding of what

00:11:49.410 --> 00:11:51.810
other children might be
experiencing around our country

00:11:51.810 --> 00:11:53.410
and around the world?

00:11:53.410 --> 00:11:57.439
And so in a
not-so-small nutshell,

00:11:57.439 --> 00:11:58.980
that's one of my
arguments for why we

00:11:58.980 --> 00:12:00.900
should talk about these topics.

00:12:00.900 --> 00:12:02.970
When our children
want to learn from us,

00:12:02.970 --> 00:12:05.430
this is a chance to help
them learn about the world,

00:12:05.430 --> 00:12:08.770
about others' experiences, to
be more compassionate to that,

00:12:08.770 --> 00:12:11.820
but then also to talk about
skills that they might need

00:12:11.820 --> 00:12:14.070
when they face those
challenges, or if they face

00:12:14.070 --> 00:12:16.052
those challenges in the future.

00:12:16.052 --> 00:12:17.787
DAVID LEVIN: So given--

00:12:17.787 --> 00:12:20.370
let's say we buy this, that we
should have that conversation--

00:12:20.370 --> 00:12:22.369
what are some strategies
that we can use to have

00:12:22.369 --> 00:12:23.580
these types of conversations?

00:12:23.580 --> 00:12:25.410
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Sure.

00:12:25.410 --> 00:12:29.940
So in the book, I
break down the sections

00:12:29.940 --> 00:12:32.260
into different types
of conversations.

00:12:32.260 --> 00:12:36.900
And one set of conversations
is really about emotions,

00:12:36.900 --> 00:12:40.510
and how we help children
manage those tough emotions.

00:12:40.510 --> 00:12:42.320
And I think that each of these--

00:12:42.320 --> 00:12:44.670
as I'll just briefly touch
on-- these different sections

00:12:44.670 --> 00:12:47.460
and types of conversations we
have have different strategies

00:12:47.460 --> 00:12:49.180
that go along with them.

00:12:49.180 --> 00:12:52.590
And so one of the starting
sections that I talk about

00:12:52.590 --> 00:12:56.010
in the book is how we
set up that relationship

00:12:56.010 --> 00:12:59.250
with our children,
really listening to them

00:12:59.250 --> 00:13:03.270
and giving them a chance to
share, giving them a chance

00:13:03.270 --> 00:13:05.130
to listen, and
that back and forth

00:13:05.130 --> 00:13:08.130
that goes on between
parents or other adults

00:13:08.130 --> 00:13:10.740
and the children in their lives.

00:13:10.740 --> 00:13:12.905
In that first section,
where we talk about some

00:13:12.905 --> 00:13:14.280
of these strategies
for how do we

00:13:14.280 --> 00:13:17.664
do this when our children have
those really tough emotions?

00:13:17.664 --> 00:13:19.080
That's one of the
questions that I

00:13:19.080 --> 00:13:21.930
think I'm asked most
often about parents,

00:13:21.930 --> 00:13:26.340
is how do we talk to children
about those really hard

00:13:26.340 --> 00:13:28.440
challenging emotions?

00:13:28.440 --> 00:13:33.010
And it's such a big challenge
for a lot of different reasons.

00:13:33.010 --> 00:13:35.520
So if you think about--

00:13:35.520 --> 00:13:37.740
I'm going to turn things
on you for just a moment.

00:13:37.740 --> 00:13:40.740
Those of you who have children--
most folks in the room--

00:13:40.740 --> 00:13:44.160
what are the skills
that a new baby

00:13:44.160 --> 00:13:47.119
has to communicate or
to have a conversation?

00:13:47.119 --> 00:13:49.160
How do they let us know
when they need something?

00:13:49.160 --> 00:13:50.040
AUDIENCE: Crying.

00:13:50.040 --> 00:13:50.920
AUDIENCE: Crying.

00:13:50.920 --> 00:13:54.650
SHAUNA TOMINEY: OK, just
heard the universal word, cry.

00:13:54.650 --> 00:13:55.250
What else?

00:13:55.250 --> 00:13:58.240
What else do they do?

00:13:58.240 --> 00:13:59.281
AUDIENCE: They'll fidget.

00:13:59.281 --> 00:13:59.860
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Fidget?

00:13:59.860 --> 00:13:59.990
OK.

00:13:59.990 --> 00:14:00.885
AUDIENCE: Just move around.

00:14:00.885 --> 00:14:02.426
SHAUNA TOMINEY:
Yeah, move your body?

00:14:02.426 --> 00:14:04.050
Yeah, move around.

00:14:04.050 --> 00:14:07.220
Tense, get tense, kick, scream.

00:14:07.220 --> 00:14:08.780
We hope sometimes smile.

00:14:08.780 --> 00:14:10.190
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:10.190 --> 00:14:11.820
Laugh at some point.

00:14:11.820 --> 00:14:13.970
We hope for those moments too.

00:14:13.970 --> 00:14:17.060
But when our children
are born, they

00:14:17.060 --> 00:14:20.990
are essentially programmed
to be a ball of impulses

00:14:20.990 --> 00:14:24.440
and instincts, to use their
bodies and their cries

00:14:24.440 --> 00:14:27.170
to let us know that
they need something.

00:14:27.170 --> 00:14:30.620
Now when we're talking about
how do we have conversations

00:14:30.620 --> 00:14:34.000
with young children who
are kicking and screaming

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:35.457
and they can't
talk back with us,

00:14:35.457 --> 00:14:37.790
when they get a little bit
older and all they want to do

00:14:37.790 --> 00:14:40.490
is run around with a
diaper on their head,

00:14:40.490 --> 00:14:42.870
we have to get really creative.

00:14:42.870 --> 00:14:45.410
First, we can let
them know that we're

00:14:45.410 --> 00:14:47.720
recognizing those
emotions as the way

00:14:47.720 --> 00:14:49.970
that they're
expressing themselves.

00:14:49.970 --> 00:14:52.190
And as parents,
oftentimes it's our goal

00:14:52.190 --> 00:14:55.280
to help children move from
being that child who's

00:14:55.280 --> 00:14:59.150
kicking and screaming and
tensing and sometimes smiling,

00:14:59.150 --> 00:15:03.350
to being able to say, I'm
angry, or I'm frustrated,

00:15:03.350 --> 00:15:07.010
or I'm kind of grumpy,
can you help me calm down?

00:15:07.010 --> 00:15:10.586
How many of you know
adults who can do that?

00:15:10.586 --> 00:15:12.020
[LAUGHTER]

00:15:12.020 --> 00:15:14.610
Maybe not as many as we'd like.

00:15:14.610 --> 00:15:18.470
And so in recognizing that
our children's emotions

00:15:18.470 --> 00:15:20.150
are actually--

00:15:20.150 --> 00:15:22.010
the way that they
express them are

00:15:22.010 --> 00:15:25.720
a way of communicating a need,
and then talking about that,

00:15:25.720 --> 00:15:28.886
labeling it, being able
to use words ourselves,

00:15:28.886 --> 00:15:30.260
and to be a role
model in the way

00:15:30.260 --> 00:15:33.470
that we talk about our
own emotions to help them

00:15:33.470 --> 00:15:35.180
learn to do that.

00:15:35.180 --> 00:15:37.010
And in showing our
children they can

00:15:37.010 --> 00:15:38.920
trust us to talk
about their emotions

00:15:38.920 --> 00:15:40.460
really in a teaching
kind of way,

00:15:40.460 --> 00:15:43.430
rather than a punishing
way, we can also

00:15:43.430 --> 00:15:45.920
help set the stage for
these other conversations.

00:15:45.920 --> 00:15:48.950
So for thinking about
how we go about tackling

00:15:48.950 --> 00:15:51.986
these more complex topics
as our children are ready.

00:15:51.986 --> 00:15:54.420
DAVID LEVIN: So you mentioned
emotions and handling them,

00:15:54.420 --> 00:15:56.800
and some adults have
trouble with that.

00:15:56.800 --> 00:15:59.060
So what are we do when
we're even having trouble

00:15:59.060 --> 00:16:00.260
with managing our emotions?

00:16:00.260 --> 00:16:02.240
How can we teach the
skills to our kids?

00:16:02.240 --> 00:16:03.980
SHAUNA TOMINEY: That's
a great question.

00:16:03.980 --> 00:16:06.740
Because as adults,
this isn't something

00:16:06.740 --> 00:16:08.840
that we're always
taught ourselves either,

00:16:08.840 --> 00:16:12.410
in terms of OK, when we
get really frustrated, that

00:16:12.410 --> 00:16:16.100
impulse of that kicking
and that screaming toddler

00:16:16.100 --> 00:16:18.290
still lives within us sometimes.

00:16:18.290 --> 00:16:20.120
And to really be able
to step back and say,

00:16:20.120 --> 00:16:23.690
I'm frustrated, I'm
angry, what's going on--

00:16:23.690 --> 00:16:26.730
this is a great chance to
practice thinking about, OK,

00:16:26.730 --> 00:16:29.004
what is it I want
my child to do when

00:16:29.004 --> 00:16:30.170
they're having this feeling?

00:16:30.170 --> 00:16:35.120
And what's our family emotion
rule for frustration or anger

00:16:35.120 --> 00:16:36.440
or stress?

00:16:36.440 --> 00:16:38.060
Our children have
these feelings.

00:16:38.060 --> 00:16:40.280
How can we teach them to
show it in a way that's

00:16:40.280 --> 00:16:42.632
effective and appropriate?

00:16:42.632 --> 00:16:44.090
And then coming
back to ourselves--

00:16:44.090 --> 00:16:46.170
to think about well,
let's talk about this.

00:16:46.170 --> 00:16:47.380
What does this look like?

00:16:47.380 --> 00:16:50.446
And now I should be practicing
this too as a parent.

00:16:50.446 --> 00:16:52.070
So if this is our
family emotion rule--

00:16:52.070 --> 00:16:56.210
if our rule is that we're going
to try our hardest to not kick

00:16:56.210 --> 00:16:59.880
and throw and scream, but
to stop and say, I'm angry,

00:16:59.880 --> 00:17:01.490
I've got to try that too.

00:17:01.490 --> 00:17:04.190
And when I don't,
then think about--

00:17:04.190 --> 00:17:07.400
all right, when my child
can't do this either,

00:17:07.400 --> 00:17:08.810
what do I want them to do?

00:17:08.810 --> 00:17:11.390
To step back and say, I
should have done something

00:17:11.390 --> 00:17:12.530
differently.

00:17:12.530 --> 00:17:15.140
And our child will never
do that, or a teenager--

00:17:15.140 --> 00:17:17.042
imagine them coming in
and saying, you know,

00:17:17.042 --> 00:17:19.250
last night when you wouldn't
let me take the car out,

00:17:19.250 --> 00:17:22.160
and I got so mad and I
just started yelling--

00:17:22.160 --> 00:17:23.780
Dad, I shouldn't have done that.

00:17:23.780 --> 00:17:25.700
Next time, I'm going
to take a deep breath

00:17:25.700 --> 00:17:28.380
and I'm going to come to you
and tell you how I'm feeling.

00:17:28.380 --> 00:17:30.020
Can you imagine a
teenager doing that?

00:17:30.020 --> 00:17:31.490
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:31.490 --> 00:17:35.600
They won't unless we do that
and model it for them first.

00:17:35.600 --> 00:17:38.156
It's going to take a lot
of work, but it's worth it.

00:17:38.156 --> 00:17:40.280
DAVID LEVIN: So I'm going
to keep asking questions.

00:17:40.280 --> 00:17:40.470
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Sure.

