00:17:46.013 --> 00:17:49.180
and we'll start to mix those in.

00:17:49.180 --> 00:17:50.930
And if not, we'll just
keep going up here.

00:17:50.930 --> 00:17:54.380
You can listen to the
two of us talking.

00:17:54.380 --> 00:17:55.485
So when I read this--

00:17:55.485 --> 00:17:57.110
I read it pretty much
straight through,

00:17:57.110 --> 00:17:58.340
given the timing and all.

00:17:58.340 --> 00:18:01.246
And I almost felt overwhelmed
by the amount of information

00:18:01.246 --> 00:18:02.870
here, and trying to
think about it all.

00:18:02.870 --> 00:18:05.180
How would you recommend
that people can kind of

00:18:05.180 --> 00:18:06.884
absorb it and apply it best?

00:18:06.884 --> 00:18:08.550
SHAUNA TOMINEY: That's
a great question.

00:18:08.550 --> 00:18:11.150
There's a lot of
information in this book.

00:18:11.150 --> 00:18:12.890
And it's divided
up, as I mentioned,

00:18:12.890 --> 00:18:15.230
into different sections
that tackle different kinds

00:18:15.230 --> 00:18:16.140
of conversations.

00:18:16.140 --> 00:18:19.089
So one section is on those
foundational conversations

00:18:19.089 --> 00:18:21.380
about letting our children
know that they can trust us,

00:18:21.380 --> 00:18:23.180
that we love them,
that we're going

00:18:23.180 --> 00:18:27.110
to manage their emotions in a
way that's teaching and guiding

00:18:27.110 --> 00:18:28.835
rather than punitive.

00:18:28.835 --> 00:18:32.960
Another section on
self-awareness and acceptance,

00:18:32.960 --> 00:18:35.960
and really helping children
learn about the qualities

00:18:35.960 --> 00:18:39.470
that will make them who
they are, to those qualities

00:18:39.470 --> 00:18:40.950
that make others who they are.

00:18:40.950 --> 00:18:43.160
And those conversations
include topics

00:18:43.160 --> 00:18:48.080
like sex, gender, gender
identity, race, culture,

00:18:48.080 --> 00:18:50.270
different types of families.

00:18:50.270 --> 00:18:53.030
And then moving into another
section on conversations

00:18:53.030 --> 00:18:55.700
that focus on tough
topics, like you mentioned,

00:18:55.700 --> 00:19:01.739
Dave, divorce, death,
suicide, guns, stress, sex,

00:19:01.739 --> 00:19:03.280
some of these
challenging topics that

00:19:03.280 --> 00:19:05.650
come up over time, and
sometimes earlier than we

00:19:05.650 --> 00:19:07.570
expect with our children.

00:19:07.570 --> 00:19:09.910
And then the final section
is on these conversations

00:19:09.910 --> 00:19:12.940
that help us think about all
that we've been learning,

00:19:12.940 --> 00:19:16.510
and applying that to
friendships, to relationships

00:19:16.510 --> 00:19:18.160
inside and outside
of the family,

00:19:18.160 --> 00:19:20.350
to recognizing privilege,
to really thinking

00:19:20.350 --> 00:19:23.200
about how do we find our
voice and make a difference?

00:19:23.200 --> 00:19:28.240
And along with that come very
specific and concrete ideas,

00:19:28.240 --> 00:19:31.420
so storybook recommendations
with discussion questions,

00:19:31.420 --> 00:19:35.020
family activities,
parenting Q &amp; A's.

00:19:35.020 --> 00:19:38.350
With all of that being
packed into one book,

00:19:38.350 --> 00:19:43.810
I really encourage folks to pick
it up and take a look at what's

00:19:43.810 --> 00:19:45.230
helpful at different times.

00:19:45.230 --> 00:19:48.260
It's the kind of book that
you can read straight through.

00:19:48.260 --> 00:19:52.060
But it may be hard to go through
and really think about, now

00:19:52.060 --> 00:19:54.760
how do I apply this at home
if you're not taking it little

00:19:54.760 --> 00:19:55.280
by little.

00:19:55.280 --> 00:19:56.821
So it's the kind of
book that's meant

00:19:56.821 --> 00:19:58.660
to be taken in snippets
if it's helpful.

00:19:58.660 --> 00:20:00.626
DAVID LEVIN: Yeah,
really, I guess I

00:20:00.626 --> 00:20:01.750
like two things about that.

00:20:01.750 --> 00:20:03.849
One, I like the index in back.

00:20:03.849 --> 00:20:05.890
So if you're having some
struggle with some topic

00:20:05.890 --> 00:20:07.720
or whatever, you can look back
there and see if it's covered.

00:20:07.720 --> 00:20:08.430
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Absolutely.

00:20:08.430 --> 00:20:09.540
DAVID LEVIN: And two,
like you mentioned,

00:20:09.540 --> 00:20:10.690
at the end of the
chapters, there's

00:20:10.690 --> 00:20:11.740
the book recommendations.

00:20:11.740 --> 00:20:13.780
How do those tie in
and help with you

00:20:13.780 --> 00:20:16.180
understanding or working
through the topics better?

00:20:16.180 --> 00:20:19.420
SHAUNA TOMINEY: So
storybooks are a great way

00:20:19.420 --> 00:20:22.330
to tackle topics that
we might not otherwise

00:20:22.330 --> 00:20:24.250
feel prepared to talk
about with our children.

00:20:24.250 --> 00:20:26.080
It can be a great
way to also take

00:20:26.080 --> 00:20:29.310
a look at challenges like
challenging emotions, anger

00:20:29.310 --> 00:20:32.110
or frustration, outside of those
emotionally charged moments.

00:20:32.110 --> 00:20:34.480
If our children are in the
middle of a tantrum, that's

00:20:34.480 --> 00:20:36.562
not always the best
time to say, oh,

00:20:36.562 --> 00:20:38.020
I can see you're
really frustrated.

00:20:38.020 --> 00:20:40.822
Let's talk about what
you should do instead.

00:20:40.822 --> 00:20:42.280
They're going to
keep on tantruming

00:20:42.280 --> 00:20:43.630
and kicking and screaming.

00:20:43.630 --> 00:20:45.640
They are emotionally charged.

00:20:45.640 --> 00:20:47.950
They are in that fight,
flight, or freeze mode--

00:20:47.950 --> 00:20:50.650
not so much freeze,
more of that fight mode.

00:20:50.650 --> 00:20:52.150
And they're not listening.

00:20:52.150 --> 00:20:53.270
They're not learning.

00:20:53.270 --> 00:20:57.700
But we can use books to pull out
of that situation and say, OK--

00:20:57.700 --> 00:21:00.580
oh, look what made this
character field really angry

00:21:00.580 --> 00:21:02.590
or frustrated or disappointed.

00:21:02.590 --> 00:21:04.210
Have you ever felt that way?

00:21:04.210 --> 00:21:06.460
What do we do when
we feel that way?

00:21:06.460 --> 00:21:08.210
So that's one way.

00:21:08.210 --> 00:21:13.600
Another way that I think books
and storybooks are so important

00:21:13.600 --> 00:21:15.490
is it's a way to build
empathy, to learn

00:21:15.490 --> 00:21:18.940
about others' experiences, to
be able to bring in role models

00:21:18.940 --> 00:21:23.500
to your child's life of
people who look like they do,

00:21:23.500 --> 00:21:26.590
who think like they
do, dress like they do,

00:21:26.590 --> 00:21:29.680
have a family that
looks like theirs.

00:21:29.680 --> 00:21:31.930
And that's harder
to do for children

00:21:31.930 --> 00:21:34.570
who come from a
non-dominant culture,

00:21:34.570 --> 00:21:36.834
or who have a
non-dominant family type.

00:21:36.834 --> 00:21:38.500
We have to really
work hard to make sure

00:21:38.500 --> 00:21:43.440
our children have role
models who look like they do,

00:21:43.440 --> 00:21:45.280
so that they feel
valued, so that they

00:21:45.280 --> 00:21:46.912
feel like part of a community.

00:21:46.912 --> 00:21:48.370
And I think the
last thing I'll say

00:21:48.370 --> 00:21:51.280
about that is I think it's
important for children who come

00:21:51.280 --> 00:21:53.590
from dominant groups
and dominant cultures

00:21:53.590 --> 00:21:57.760
also to have those role models
from minority and non-dominant

00:21:57.760 --> 00:22:00.700
groups so that those children
see one another as part

00:22:00.700 --> 00:22:02.650
of that same community too.

00:22:02.650 --> 00:22:04.480
So I've tried really
hard in this book

00:22:04.480 --> 00:22:08.500
to come up with a wide range
of storybook recommendations

00:22:08.500 --> 00:22:10.570
that really depict
children and families

00:22:10.570 --> 00:22:12.580
in different
situations, experiencing

00:22:12.580 --> 00:22:14.710
different challenges
and strengths,

00:22:14.710 --> 00:22:17.120
so that we can have those
role models for our children.

00:22:17.120 --> 00:22:17.820
DAVID LEVIN: Sounds great.

00:22:17.820 --> 00:22:18.930
I think we have a question.

00:22:18.930 --> 00:22:19.385
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Sure.

00:22:19.385 --> 00:22:21.070
AUDIENCE: So my
question is around kind

00:22:21.070 --> 00:22:22.169
of like the age range.

00:22:22.169 --> 00:22:23.710
I'm sure the skill
system and methods

00:22:23.710 --> 00:22:26.410
that you talk about in
your book apply to children

00:22:26.410 --> 00:22:27.770
throughout their lives.

00:22:27.770 --> 00:22:30.400
But would you say that
there is a cutoff,

00:22:30.400 --> 00:22:33.280
or an age range where these
conversations become really

00:22:33.280 --> 00:22:38.130
crucial or have a lasting
impact on kind of, I guess,

00:22:38.130 --> 00:22:40.630
how compassionate
children become?

00:22:40.630 --> 00:22:43.100
SHAUNA TOMINEY: That's
a great question.

00:22:43.100 --> 00:22:46.540
I think that just to tackle age
range, the book, I would say,

00:22:46.540 --> 00:22:49.755
is ideal in the 0 to
8 or 9 age range is

00:22:49.755 --> 00:22:51.880
where I'd put it in terms
of where the conversation

00:22:51.880 --> 00:22:53.950
examples are coming
from, as well as

00:22:53.950 --> 00:22:56.570
where the storybooks
are the best fit.

00:22:56.570 --> 00:22:58.780
But I think it's
also never too late.

00:22:58.780 --> 00:23:01.750
It's never too late
to have a conversation

00:23:01.750 --> 00:23:04.060
or to build a relationship
with your child

00:23:04.060 --> 00:23:07.120
where you can help them
practice these skills.

00:23:07.120 --> 00:23:09.550
We've got to look at
compassion like a scale

00:23:09.550 --> 00:23:11.980
or a set of skills,
just like anything else,

00:23:11.980 --> 00:23:14.440
just like emotion regulation,
just like anything

00:23:14.440 --> 00:23:16.150
that we're learning
and practicing.

00:23:16.150 --> 00:23:20.470
And it may be harder
later on if children

00:23:20.470 --> 00:23:22.330
haven't had a lot of practice.

00:23:22.330 --> 00:23:23.800
But again, it's never too late.

00:23:23.800 --> 00:23:26.670
I once had a parent sitting in
a workshop with me who said,

00:23:26.670 --> 00:23:28.990
so I've got teenage
boys at home,

00:23:28.990 --> 00:23:31.510
and the stuff you're
talking about emotions

00:23:31.510 --> 00:23:33.770
and how we talk about it,
I want to do that now.

00:23:33.770 --> 00:23:34.910
So what do I do?

00:23:34.910 --> 00:23:37.390
Do I just go home and say,
this is how we roll now,

00:23:37.390 --> 00:23:40.600
and we're just going to talk
about emotions from now on?

00:23:40.600 --> 00:23:42.760
And it was a real question
that he was asking.

00:23:42.760 --> 00:23:44.920
Because he hadn't been
doing this at home.

00:23:44.920 --> 00:23:47.890
And he said, well, what do I do
if I now see the value in this

00:23:47.890 --> 00:23:49.960
and I just want
to change things?

00:23:49.960 --> 00:23:53.470
And a big part of that
is putting yourself

00:23:53.470 --> 00:23:54.680
up as a role model.

00:23:54.680 --> 00:23:56.930
And so coming home and opening
yourself up and saying,

00:23:56.930 --> 00:23:59.100
OK, I had a tough
day at work today,

00:23:59.100 --> 00:24:01.019
and I kind of want
to talk about this.

00:24:01.019 --> 00:24:03.060
Did anyone else have these
kinds of feelings too?

00:24:03.060 --> 00:24:05.350
What do you think I
should do about this?

00:24:05.350 --> 00:24:08.210
So I hope that
answers your question.

00:24:08.210 --> 00:24:10.150
DAVID LEVIN: And we'll
go to their question.

00:24:10.150 --> 00:24:12.840
But I think one thing
that I got out of it

00:24:12.840 --> 00:24:15.464
is that it's really
good that you start

00:24:15.464 --> 00:24:17.630
from a very young age, even
before your children are

00:24:17.630 --> 00:24:21.500
non-verbal and so on, to start
to have these conversations.

00:24:21.500 --> 00:24:23.400
And I think you're
emphasizing that,

00:24:23.400 --> 00:24:25.440
that that's where the
trust comes from and so

00:24:25.440 --> 00:24:27.226
on, just continuing throughout.

00:24:27.226 --> 00:24:28.350
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Absolutely.

00:24:28.350 --> 00:24:30.300
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:24:30.300 --> 00:24:31.830
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:24:31.830 --> 00:24:35.880
What are your thoughts about
a conversation with children

00:24:35.880 --> 00:24:39.180
about their relationship
with technology,

00:24:39.180 --> 00:24:42.420
so that they are in
control and use tech

00:24:42.420 --> 00:24:47.130
as their tools to
achieve their goals?

00:24:47.130 --> 00:24:50.160
Because otherwise,
a parent that stands

00:24:50.160 --> 00:24:51.990
in the way between
a child and a screen

00:24:51.990 --> 00:24:56.640
can cause strong
emotions in a child.

00:24:56.640 --> 00:25:00.260
I think that's a sight
that can be often found.

00:25:00.260 --> 00:25:01.800
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Yeah.

00:25:01.800 --> 00:25:02.920
That's a great question.

00:25:02.920 --> 00:25:06.150
I think technology is such
a big part of our lives,

00:25:06.150 --> 00:25:08.010
and such a big part of
our children's lives,

00:25:08.010 --> 00:25:11.430
and even more so for them now
than it was for us growing up.

00:25:11.430 --> 00:25:15.150
And society is continuing
to move in that direction.

00:25:15.150 --> 00:25:17.770
And I touch a little
bit on technology.

00:25:17.770 --> 00:25:19.920
I don't have it as a
specific topic in the book.

00:25:19.920 --> 00:25:21.760
I mention it a little
bit here and there.

00:25:21.760 --> 00:25:24.430
But I think that like
with anything else,

00:25:24.430 --> 00:25:26.100
we have to be a role
model, in looking

00:25:26.100 --> 00:25:31.860
at how do we be a good
citizen in using technology?

00:25:31.860 --> 00:25:35.040
What are all of the
strengths that technology

00:25:35.040 --> 00:25:36.580
brings to our lives?

00:25:36.580 --> 00:25:38.550
What are the capacities
that it brings?

00:25:38.550 --> 00:25:41.490
What are all of those
tools that can really

00:25:41.490 --> 00:25:45.390
enhance what we're doing, our
effectiveness, our efficiency?

00:25:45.390 --> 00:25:47.820
But then also looking at what
are some of the challenges?

00:25:47.820 --> 00:25:49.861
So some of the ways that
technology is coming out

00:25:49.861 --> 00:25:52.800
as problematic is
in cyberbullying,

00:25:52.800 --> 00:25:54.300
or in some of the
ways that children

00:25:54.300 --> 00:25:57.150
are relating to
each other outside

00:25:57.150 --> 00:25:58.410
of those personal moments.

00:25:58.410 --> 00:26:01.020
Sometimes we interact with one
another in a different way when

00:26:01.020 --> 00:26:02.789
it comes out over technology.

00:26:02.789 --> 00:26:04.830
And I really try to think
about it in my own life

00:26:04.830 --> 00:26:08.310
too as a parent, modeling what
we want to see in our children.

00:26:08.310 --> 00:26:10.440
So thinking about, if
we want our children

00:26:10.440 --> 00:26:13.050
to set limits around
the time or the way

00:26:13.050 --> 00:26:16.380
that they're using technology,
we have to model that too.

00:26:16.380 --> 00:26:19.960
We have to talk about it, share
those family values around it.

00:26:19.960 --> 00:26:21.760
What are our rules with that?

00:26:21.760 --> 00:26:24.270
And then also
thinking about how do

00:26:24.270 --> 00:26:27.030
we engage our children in
that technology in a really

00:26:27.030 --> 00:26:27.910
healthy way?

00:26:27.910 --> 00:26:31.800
So one of the things that, for
me, as a parent, for example--

00:26:31.800 --> 00:26:33.570
and I know many of you
as parents probably

00:26:33.570 --> 00:26:35.197
think about this too--

00:26:35.197 --> 00:26:37.530
when it's the first day of
school, what do I want to do?

00:26:37.530 --> 00:26:41.170
Take a picture and put
it up on social media.

00:26:41.170 --> 00:26:43.500
My daughter has not wanted
me to take a picture

00:26:43.500 --> 00:26:46.810
and put it on social media
for the last three years.

00:26:46.810 --> 00:26:48.300
So since she was
in kindergarten,

00:26:48.300 --> 00:26:51.030
I have not posted a first
day of school picture,

00:26:51.030 --> 00:26:53.220
as much as I've wanted to.

00:26:53.220 --> 00:26:54.450
And that's hard as a parent.

00:26:54.450 --> 00:26:57.330
Because I think, well,
this is my life too.

00:26:57.330 --> 00:27:00.300
But it's also hers, to
decide how she's shown,

00:27:00.300 --> 00:27:01.500
and how she's depicted.

00:27:01.500 --> 00:27:05.670
And that I've seen as just
one little lesson in terms

00:27:05.670 --> 00:27:08.430
of saying, OK, you've
got to remember,

00:27:08.430 --> 00:27:09.730
I will always do this for you.

00:27:09.730 --> 00:27:11.970
If you don't want to be
shown on social media,

00:27:11.970 --> 00:27:14.160
I won't put your
picture there, just

00:27:14.160 --> 00:27:16.740
like how you should treat other
people in the way that you

00:27:16.740 --> 00:27:20.220
talk to people, or talk about
people, or whether or not you

00:27:20.220 --> 00:27:22.050
post a picture, or
take something down

00:27:22.050 --> 00:27:23.340
when you're asked.

00:27:23.340 --> 00:27:25.410
We have to learn how to
treat people respectfully

00:27:25.410 --> 00:27:27.840
across these platforms,
while also valuing

00:27:27.840 --> 00:27:32.655
all of the amazing capacity
that technology brings.

00:27:32.655 --> 00:27:36.370
Yeah, thank you.

00:27:36.370 --> 00:27:38.620
DAVID LEVIN: I think you've
touched on it a little bit

00:27:38.620 --> 00:27:40.036
there, but in a
part of your book,

00:27:40.036 --> 00:27:41.500
you talk about I
think respecting

00:27:41.500 --> 00:27:43.960
the boundaries of
kids too, when they're

00:27:43.960 --> 00:27:46.972
talking about things like,
oh, go give that uncle a hug

00:27:46.972 --> 00:27:48.930
or whatever, and they're
like, I don't want to,

00:27:48.930 --> 00:27:51.160
and how do you deal with
this type of situation?

00:27:51.160 --> 00:27:52.630
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Sure.

00:27:52.630 --> 00:27:54.760
Well, and I think it does
relate to technology,

00:27:54.760 --> 00:27:58.180
and it relates to a lot of areas
what you're talking about too

00:27:58.180 --> 00:28:00.340
is in relation to
your body and who

00:28:00.340 --> 00:28:01.810
has control over what you do.

00:28:04.520 --> 00:28:07.940
And as we are raising our
children-- one of the reasons

00:28:07.940 --> 00:28:10.010
that I think having these
kinds of conversations

00:28:10.010 --> 00:28:13.520
is so important, and tackling
tough conversation topics

00:28:13.520 --> 00:28:15.650
is so important, is
it gives us a chance

00:28:15.650 --> 00:28:18.170
to help our children build
skills to think about

00:28:18.170 --> 00:28:19.970
what do you want and
what do you not want,

00:28:19.970 --> 00:28:22.511
and how do you speak up when
you need something or don't want

00:28:22.511 --> 00:28:23.480
something?

00:28:23.480 --> 00:28:27.200
But then also showing them
that we will follow through

00:28:27.200 --> 00:28:28.010
with that.

00:28:28.010 --> 00:28:31.980
For a child to say, I don't
want to hug that person--

00:28:31.980 --> 00:28:34.670
it's pretty common to say, no,
go and hug your grandparents,

00:28:34.670 --> 00:28:36.920
or go hug your uncle,
or go hug your aunt.

00:28:36.920 --> 00:28:38.920
But then we're telling
our child that they don't

00:28:38.920 --> 00:28:40.230
have control over their body.

00:28:40.230 --> 00:28:42.520
And if we really want them
to believe that they do,

00:28:42.520 --> 00:28:44.660
we've got to listen to that too.

00:28:44.660 --> 00:28:48.680
And I think part of having
those tough conversations

00:28:48.680 --> 00:28:54.050
into other topics as well is
learning that over time, we

00:28:54.050 --> 00:28:56.192
have to give more and
more trust to our child

00:28:56.192 --> 00:28:57.650
in terms of them
being able to make

00:28:57.650 --> 00:29:00.830
those decisions for themselves,
and them having the skills

00:29:00.830 --> 00:29:03.080
that they need to
manage conversations

00:29:03.080 --> 00:29:04.940
or tough situations
that will come up.

00:29:04.940 --> 00:29:06.520
Because we won't
always be there.

00:29:06.520 --> 00:29:10.310
DAVID LEVIN: But it is there
a possibility of giving them

00:29:10.310 --> 00:29:13.040
too much choice
and too much mand--

00:29:13.040 --> 00:29:16.765
I don't know-- kind of like
let them rule the whole thing?

00:29:16.765 --> 00:29:18.170
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Absolutely.

00:29:18.170 --> 00:29:18.750
Absolutely.

00:29:18.750 --> 00:29:21.470
I think boundaries are
also very important.

00:29:21.470 --> 00:29:22.970
We can't say to a
child, I'll listen

00:29:22.970 --> 00:29:24.620
to what you need in
terms of technology,

00:29:24.620 --> 00:29:26.578
and they say, OK, well,
I'd like to watch shows

00:29:26.578 --> 00:29:30.930
for five hours on this
device or that device.

00:29:30.930 --> 00:29:32.340
We also set boundaries.

00:29:32.340 --> 00:29:35.060
And I think as parents, we also
need to communicate our family

00:29:35.060 --> 00:29:38.060
values, whether
it is technology,

00:29:38.060 --> 00:29:44.261
or whose choices it is related
to your own body or anything

00:29:44.261 --> 00:29:44.760
else.

00:29:44.760 --> 00:29:46.520
One of the things-- just to
give an example in the book--

00:29:46.520 --> 00:29:48.978
in talking about sex, which is
a challenging topic for many

00:29:48.978 --> 00:29:51.951
families--

00:29:51.951 --> 00:29:54.200
there's been some research
showing that teens actually

00:29:54.200 --> 00:29:57.380
wish that their parents
talked more to them

00:29:57.380 --> 00:29:59.870
about family values
around sex, where they're

00:29:59.870 --> 00:30:02.930
getting a lot of talks
around safe sex practices,

00:30:02.930 --> 00:30:07.190
but not necessarily about
those family values.

00:30:07.190 --> 00:30:09.140
That's not always the case.

00:30:09.140 --> 00:30:12.297
But that has to be
a piece of this too.

00:30:12.297 --> 00:30:13.880
DAVID LEVIN: We have
another question.

00:30:13.880 --> 00:30:14.140
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Yeah.

00:30:14.140 --> 00:30:15.080
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:30:15.080 --> 00:30:17.840
My wife and I come from
a different country,

00:30:17.840 --> 00:30:20.730
and we have different
experiences growing up.

00:30:20.730 --> 00:30:22.847
Our kids grow up here.

00:30:22.847 --> 00:30:24.680
They have a much more
comfortable lifestyle,

00:30:24.680 --> 00:30:27.690
I feel like, in general,
at least I think so.

00:30:27.690 --> 00:30:29.870
So one of the difficult
conversation topics

00:30:29.870 --> 00:30:32.884
usually arise when there
is a sense of entitlement.

00:30:32.884 --> 00:30:35.300
At least my wife and I feel
like, when we were growing up,

00:30:35.300 --> 00:30:38.510
we didn't have this or that.

00:30:38.510 --> 00:30:42.185
And you kind of talked about
it earlier about storybooks.

00:30:42.185 --> 00:30:44.810
Do you have any other techniques
to kind of show them, hey, you

00:30:44.810 --> 00:30:45.310
know what?

00:30:45.310 --> 00:30:50.630
Maybe try to get a better
perspective on their situation,

00:30:50.630 --> 00:30:54.800
as far as you growing up here
versus where we grew up from.

00:30:54.800 --> 00:30:58.360
Do you have any other tools
aside from like storybooks,

00:30:58.360 --> 00:30:59.295
any other techniques?

00:30:59.295 --> 00:31:00.170
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Yeah.

00:31:00.170 --> 00:31:02.000
Well, one, that you
were talking about too

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:03.420
is sharing your
personal stories,

00:31:03.420 --> 00:31:04.920
sharing what it was
like growing up.

00:31:04.920 --> 00:31:06.050
My mom is an immigrant.

00:31:06.050 --> 00:31:06.370
She's from Taiwan.

00:31:06.370 --> 00:31:07.828
AUDIENCE: It that
tends to be like,

00:31:07.828 --> 00:31:11.136
oh, she keeps saying that again,
that again, that story again?

00:31:11.136 --> 00:31:13.760
SHAUNA TOMINEY: But also to say
this is really important for me

00:31:13.760 --> 00:31:14.510
to share with you.

00:31:14.510 --> 00:31:16.880
Because this is what it was
like when I was growing up.

00:31:16.880 --> 00:31:18.140
This is what it's like here.

00:31:18.140 --> 00:31:22.580
And I think that even in passing
through the day-- at holiday

00:31:22.580 --> 00:31:25.670
time, sometimes when it seems
like there's so much and so

00:31:25.670 --> 00:31:28.190
much more than maybe
others are experiencing,

00:31:28.190 --> 00:31:30.170
to be able to talk about
that, that we are very

00:31:30.170 --> 00:31:32.690
fortunate here, and pointing
out those things that we're

00:31:32.690 --> 00:31:35.330
really grateful for, talking
about gratitude, what it is

00:31:35.330 --> 00:31:36.590
we're thankful for.

00:31:36.590 --> 00:31:39.370
Because others don't
always have these things.

00:31:39.370 --> 00:31:41.090
And these are
things in our lives

00:31:41.090 --> 00:31:43.330
that we really appreciate.

00:31:43.330 --> 00:31:45.320
But it's hard
sometimes when you're

00:31:45.320 --> 00:31:48.800
fighting against the
excitement of new things,

00:31:48.800 --> 00:31:50.630
or having more
with young children

00:31:50.630 --> 00:31:51.870
to have those conversations.

00:31:51.870 --> 00:31:55.580
But I it's important
to continually,

00:31:55.580 --> 00:31:59.810
in a way that both allows them
to be kids and celebrate what

00:31:59.810 --> 00:32:03.110
they want to celebrate,
have that continual reminder

00:32:03.110 --> 00:32:05.660
of this is something we
should be thankful for.

00:32:05.660 --> 00:32:09.440
Writing thank you notes,
talking about gratitude,

00:32:09.440 --> 00:32:11.810
why we're grateful for things.

00:32:11.810 --> 00:32:15.560
And also-- I'll go back to
that example of storybooks--

00:32:15.560 --> 00:32:17.960
but I think it is
important to show

00:32:17.960 --> 00:32:19.955
what other children
experience, and how that's

00:32:19.955 --> 00:32:21.830
similar to and different
from your own lives,

00:32:21.830 --> 00:32:24.710
to build that empathy and
that understanding as well.

00:32:24.710 --> 00:32:28.185
Yeah, thank you.

00:32:28.185 --> 00:32:29.810
DAVID LEVIN: So you
talked a little bit

00:32:29.810 --> 00:32:32.605
in these various things about
being an example and all.

00:32:32.605 --> 00:32:33.480
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Yeah.

00:32:33.480 --> 00:32:37.910
DAVID LEVIN: And so if we want
to teach our kids compassion,

00:32:37.910 --> 00:32:42.150
is just being nice to other
people just good enough?

00:32:42.150 --> 00:32:44.460
SHAUNA TOMINEY: It's a start.

00:32:44.460 --> 00:32:46.230
It's a good start.

00:32:46.230 --> 00:32:50.490
And it's amazing to see how much
or how little children pick up

00:32:50.490 --> 00:32:52.077
on.

00:32:52.077 --> 00:32:53.910
One of the examples I
used in the book, just

00:32:53.910 --> 00:32:55.980
a simple example,
was holding the door

00:32:55.980 --> 00:32:57.305
open for somebody else.

00:32:57.305 --> 00:33:00.620
If you hold the door open for
somebody else and your child's

00:33:00.620 --> 00:33:03.390
standing there right next
to you, so you think,

00:33:03.390 --> 00:33:06.510
they are seeing me stand here
and being a good role model.

00:33:06.510 --> 00:33:09.870
Your child may be thinking,
why are you taking so long?

00:33:09.870 --> 00:33:13.170
I want to get home, or
I want to go to school,

00:33:13.170 --> 00:33:15.160
if you don't talk about it.

00:33:15.160 --> 00:33:19.110
And so speaking those words and
what's going on in your head

00:33:19.110 --> 00:33:21.840
out loud in terms of holding
the door open, and saying,

00:33:21.840 --> 00:33:23.590
you know, I'm going
to hold the door open,

00:33:23.590 --> 00:33:25.173
because I see this
person coming who's

00:33:25.173 --> 00:33:27.120
holding a lot of
bags in their arms,

00:33:27.120 --> 00:33:29.182
and it looks really heavy.

00:33:29.182 --> 00:33:30.640
So I'm going to
hold the door open,

00:33:30.640 --> 00:33:33.130
because I'd like to
be helpful for them.

00:33:33.130 --> 00:33:35.760
And I think that what they're
doing looks really hard.

00:33:35.760 --> 00:33:41.070
You start speaking that
inside voice out loud.

00:33:41.070 --> 00:33:44.250
It's something that makes
other adults crazy in terms

00:33:44.250 --> 00:33:46.650
of, oh, let me move
the chair for you,

00:33:46.650 --> 00:33:49.290
because I see that you
are coming back this way,

00:33:49.290 --> 00:33:51.799
and you weren't quite far
enough, and so I wanted to--

00:33:51.799 --> 00:33:52.965
it makes other adults crazy.

00:33:52.965 --> 00:33:53.850
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:53.850 --> 00:33:57.480
But it's really good for
kids to hear that language.

00:33:57.480 --> 00:33:59.670
And the same thing goes
for the previous question

00:33:59.670 --> 00:34:03.730
that we just had in
terms of saying out loud.

00:34:03.730 --> 00:34:05.430
I think I'm only
going to do this,

00:34:05.430 --> 00:34:06.930
or I'm only going
to take this much,

00:34:06.930 --> 00:34:09.449
or I'm not going to buy
anything new because I

00:34:09.449 --> 00:34:10.980
feel like we have enough.

00:34:10.980 --> 00:34:14.790
Expressing those words
out loud not only

00:34:14.790 --> 00:34:17.010
helps children see those
examples of compassion

00:34:17.010 --> 00:34:20.429
a little bit more, but it
teaches them how to think.

00:34:20.429 --> 00:34:22.949
It teaches them how to stop
and think about somebody else's

00:34:22.949 --> 00:34:25.432
feelings first, yeah.

00:34:25.432 --> 00:34:27.792
DAVID LEVIN: I think we
have another question.

00:34:27.792 --> 00:34:29.880
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:34:29.880 --> 00:34:37.650
So I have teenage girls at
home, and still two years apart.

00:34:37.650 --> 00:34:40.889
And outside, they're nice,
they're the best girls.

00:34:40.889 --> 00:34:43.210
And out with my family,
it's always perfect.

00:34:43.210 --> 00:34:44.190
But at home--

00:34:44.190 --> 00:34:45.500
[LAUGHTER]

00:34:45.500 --> 00:34:49.650
--between each other, it's
a very different story.

00:34:49.650 --> 00:34:51.600
And I'm not going to
repeat some of the things

00:34:51.600 --> 00:34:53.172
that they call each other.

00:34:53.172 --> 00:34:56.800
[LAUGHTER]

00:34:57.650 --> 00:34:59.430
And I make sure that
they understand,

00:34:59.430 --> 00:35:00.890
OK, this is what
happened at home,

00:35:00.890 --> 00:35:03.750
and I'm going to say don't
say that to your sister,

00:35:03.750 --> 00:35:05.220
it's not appropriate.

00:35:05.220 --> 00:35:07.840
And they also
acknowledge that no, they

00:35:07.840 --> 00:35:11.420
are not using these words
or these behaviors outside.

00:35:11.420 --> 00:35:12.670
They understand that.

00:35:12.670 --> 00:35:15.420
My hope is that it's
going to continue.

00:35:15.420 --> 00:35:19.920
It's going to be true at home
and true outside as well.

00:35:19.920 --> 00:35:23.390
Any recommendation on how
to deal with this situation?

00:35:23.390 --> 00:35:24.900
SHAUNA TOMINEY:
Well, one, I think

00:35:24.900 --> 00:35:26.970
celebrating what's
happening outside the home,

00:35:26.970 --> 00:35:29.490
in terms of
everyone's doing well,

00:35:29.490 --> 00:35:33.760
and by all appearances
outside, folks are like,

00:35:33.760 --> 00:35:35.890
oh, they've got it all together.

00:35:35.890 --> 00:35:37.770
And I think that happens
so often in families

00:35:37.770 --> 00:35:39.269
too, especially
with young children.

00:35:39.269 --> 00:35:42.180
Has anyone had that
experience where home just

00:35:42.180 --> 00:35:45.780
feels like it's falling apart
and a mess, and then folks say,

00:35:45.780 --> 00:35:49.980
your child is so sweet, and
doing so well, and so kind,

00:35:49.980 --> 00:35:52.020
and you think, really?

00:35:52.020 --> 00:35:52.785
Thank goodness!

00:35:52.785 --> 00:35:53.880
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:53.880 --> 00:35:56.200
And some of that
is that it's hard.

00:35:56.200 --> 00:35:59.700
It's a lot of work to
really manage your emotions,

00:35:59.700 --> 00:36:00.990
to manage your behaviors.

00:36:00.990 --> 00:36:04.040
To keep a check on what
you're saying all the time

00:36:04.040 --> 00:36:05.290
is hard to do.

00:36:05.290 --> 00:36:06.490
It takes a lot of energy.

00:36:06.490 --> 00:36:07.690
It takes a lot of intensity.

00:36:07.690 --> 00:36:11.130
It takes a lot of
brainpower for our children.

00:36:11.130 --> 00:36:13.080
And so knowing that
by the time they

00:36:13.080 --> 00:36:14.940
come home that
they're exhausted.

00:36:14.940 --> 00:36:17.050
They may be just done.

00:36:17.050 --> 00:36:19.530
The fact is they can do it.

00:36:19.530 --> 00:36:21.570
And you're seeing it
happen outside of the home,

00:36:21.570 --> 00:36:22.528
so you know it's there.

00:36:22.528 --> 00:36:23.920
So one, celebrate that.

00:36:23.920 --> 00:36:25.260
So that's great.

00:36:25.260 --> 00:36:28.650
And two recognize that, yeah,
I think that that's probably

00:36:28.650 --> 00:36:31.170
true across many families,
that we don't always

00:36:31.170 --> 00:36:33.930
treat each other within our
families as compassionately

00:36:33.930 --> 00:36:36.150
as we treat people
outside of our families.

00:36:36.150 --> 00:36:38.160
And that hopefully,
that'll grow and change

00:36:38.160 --> 00:36:41.310
as you continue to have those
conversations about what we do,

00:36:41.310 --> 00:36:44.190
what we don't do, what
we value as a family.

00:36:44.190 --> 00:36:48.780
And opening up some of
those conversations about,

00:36:48.780 --> 00:36:49.907
how was your day?

00:36:49.907 --> 00:36:51.240
What are you thinking about now?

00:36:51.240 --> 00:36:56.030
Helping them connect when
they can in different ways.

00:36:56.030 --> 00:36:59.587
That wasn't a really
specific answer,

00:36:59.587 --> 00:37:01.420
but I'd be happy to
talk more afterward too.

00:37:01.420 --> 00:37:02.215
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:37:02.215 --> 00:37:03.298
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Thank you.

00:37:03.298 --> 00:37:05.960
DAVID LEVIN: I
know in my family,

00:37:05.960 --> 00:37:07.930
I have two kids that I'm--

00:37:07.930 --> 00:37:09.308
anyway, I can relate.

00:37:09.308 --> 00:37:11.500
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:11.500 --> 00:37:13.470
But I [INAUDIBLE] reading
something your book,

00:37:13.470 --> 00:37:15.354
and you were talking
about how you

00:37:15.354 --> 00:37:16.770
had a situation
with two kids that

00:37:16.770 --> 00:37:19.430
were kind of arguing and so on.

00:37:19.430 --> 00:37:22.620
And I know my tendency at
times has been to kind of jump

00:37:22.620 --> 00:37:23.830
in and solve things.

00:37:23.830 --> 00:37:26.550
So I jump right in
and kind of like--

00:37:26.550 --> 00:37:29.340
but I think in your book,
you had a different type

00:37:29.340 --> 00:37:30.320
of scenario going.

00:37:30.320 --> 00:37:31.654
Can you tell us more about that?

00:37:31.654 --> 00:37:32.528
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Sure.

00:37:32.528 --> 00:37:34.710
I think there has to be
a blend and a balance.

00:37:34.710 --> 00:37:36.217
And just like with
anything else,

00:37:36.217 --> 00:37:37.800
we want to make sure
our children have

00:37:37.800 --> 00:37:40.650
the skills they need to
navigate different situations.

00:37:40.650 --> 00:37:43.780
And so in navigating
sibling rivalry,

00:37:43.780 --> 00:37:46.430
do we jump in right
away and say, OK, I

00:37:46.430 --> 00:37:47.550
told you not to do that.

00:37:47.550 --> 00:37:49.620
You go to your room,
you go to your room,

00:37:49.620 --> 00:37:51.330
let's just break it up.

00:37:51.330 --> 00:37:53.720
Versus helping them figure
out how to problem solve,

00:37:53.720 --> 00:37:55.720
and how to come together
and say, wait a minute,

00:37:55.720 --> 00:37:56.720
what happened?

00:37:56.720 --> 00:37:57.720
Let's talk through this.

00:37:57.720 --> 00:38:00.210
And when children are younger,
being there to guide them

00:38:00.210 --> 00:38:02.580
through what happened.

00:38:02.580 --> 00:38:04.080
Why don't you tell
me what happened?

00:38:04.080 --> 00:38:06.090
Why don't you tell
me what happened?

00:38:06.090 --> 00:38:07.420
How are you feeling about this?

00:38:07.420 --> 00:38:09.210
How are they feeling about this?

00:38:09.210 --> 00:38:12.180
To really get children to focus
on one another's feelings,

00:38:12.180 --> 00:38:14.140
and to think about one
another's situations,

00:38:14.140 --> 00:38:17.550
which can be really hard in
those sibling conflict moments.

00:38:17.550 --> 00:38:20.141
And so looking at how do
we build a relationship so

00:38:20.141 --> 00:38:22.140
that they're really
thinking about one another's

00:38:22.140 --> 00:38:25.800
feelings inside and outside
these conflict moments?

00:38:25.800 --> 00:38:28.710
And it's one of these things
that we scaffold over time,

00:38:28.710 --> 00:38:32.490
where we play more of a
role early on, again, trying

00:38:32.490 --> 00:38:35.940
to avoid some of the well,
let's just stop the scenario

00:38:35.940 --> 00:38:38.440
and get out of this, because I
can't deal with this anymore.

00:38:38.440 --> 00:38:39.731
And that will happen sometimes.

00:38:39.731 --> 00:38:41.890
Because we'll be too
tired to do anything else.

00:38:41.890 --> 00:38:43.080
And that's OK.

00:38:43.080 --> 00:38:48.219
But if we can also add in these,
OK, let's talk through this,

00:38:48.219 --> 00:38:50.760
scaffolding that so our children
start learning those skills,

00:38:50.760 --> 00:38:53.481
so that they can learn
to do that on their own.

00:38:53.481 --> 00:38:56.230
DAVID LEVIN: So you
mentioned this a little bit

00:38:56.230 --> 00:38:58.200
when we were talking
about bullying, kind

00:38:58.200 --> 00:38:59.580
of touching on it somewhat.

00:38:59.580 --> 00:39:01.740
But how can we
teach our children

00:39:01.740 --> 00:39:04.140
to stand up for
themselves and others

00:39:04.140 --> 00:39:06.630
when they're hitting
those types of scenarios?

00:39:06.630 --> 00:39:08.220
SHAUNA TOMINEY: It's
a great question.

00:39:08.220 --> 00:39:09.030
And I think it's
something that's

00:39:09.030 --> 00:39:11.070
starting to get a lot
more attention now

00:39:11.070 --> 00:39:14.392
with conversations about how do
we help children be upstanders

00:39:14.392 --> 00:39:16.350
rather than bystanders,
or different terms that

00:39:16.350 --> 00:39:17.740
are being used.

00:39:17.740 --> 00:39:20.880
And one of the ways comes
back to that foundation.

00:39:20.880 --> 00:39:27.420
When we show our children
that we are listening to them,

00:39:27.420 --> 00:39:30.930
we are taking their feelings
and their words seriously,

00:39:30.930 --> 00:39:33.344
they learn that adults
will do that for them.

00:39:33.344 --> 00:39:35.260
And not all children
have that in their lives.

00:39:35.260 --> 00:39:36.960
And so if repeatedly,
they've been

00:39:36.960 --> 00:39:39.480
shown that regardless of
the feelings they've had

00:39:39.480 --> 00:39:42.750
or the words they've
shared, no one's listened,

00:39:42.750 --> 00:39:45.240
they're probably less likely
to be able to stand up

00:39:45.240 --> 00:39:46.377
in those situations.

00:39:46.377 --> 00:39:48.210
And so if we've really
built this foundation

00:39:48.210 --> 00:39:50.640
to show children that
we take them seriously

00:39:50.640 --> 00:39:53.020
and we're here to
listen to them,

00:39:53.020 --> 00:39:56.410
they're more likely in those
moments to be able to do that.

00:39:56.410 --> 00:39:58.557
But then we also have to
help them prepare for it.

00:39:58.557 --> 00:40:00.390
So if you think about
a situation that might

00:40:00.390 --> 00:40:02.940
be challenging for a child--

00:40:02.940 --> 00:40:05.730
if you're seeing an instance
of bullying for the first time,

00:40:05.730 --> 00:40:07.680
or somebody getting
hurt, or somebody

00:40:07.680 --> 00:40:08.710
being treated unfairly.

00:40:08.710 --> 00:40:10.380
If you've never thought
about that before, but all

00:40:10.380 --> 00:40:11.963
of a sudden you see
it, and you think,

00:40:11.963 --> 00:40:15.090
oh, that doesn't feel
good, I don't like that.

00:40:15.090 --> 00:40:17.130
If we've had those
conversations--

00:40:17.130 --> 00:40:20.220
let's say we've read storybooks,
or we've played with dolls,

00:40:20.220 --> 00:40:21.750
or role-played
different scenarios

00:40:21.750 --> 00:40:23.166
that might be
challenging, or even

00:40:23.166 --> 00:40:25.620
talked about different movies
that we've watched together

00:40:25.620 --> 00:40:28.140
or TV shows, and talked
about what would you

00:40:28.140 --> 00:40:29.920
do in that moment?

00:40:29.920 --> 00:40:32.505
We can help our children
learn scripts so they can say.

00:40:32.505 --> 00:40:35.910
We can help them learn
and practice saying, hey,

00:40:35.910 --> 00:40:37.050
cut that out.

00:40:37.050 --> 00:40:41.220
Or help them learn and think
about, well, I don't feel good.

00:40:41.220 --> 00:40:43.510
I wouldn't feel good
standing up and saying that.

00:40:43.510 --> 00:40:45.930
But I would feel OK going
and telling a teacher,

00:40:45.930 --> 00:40:48.420
or going in and asking
an adult for help.

00:40:48.420 --> 00:40:50.730
So if we help our children
outside of those moments

00:40:50.730 --> 00:40:53.290
think about what they
would do in those moments,

00:40:53.290 --> 00:40:56.384
they're more likely
to see it through.

00:40:56.384 --> 00:40:59.015
DAVID LEVIN: So we're getting
close to the end of our time,

00:40:59.015 --> 00:41:01.870
so I'll ask you some
general questions.

00:41:01.870 --> 00:41:03.795
Do you have any other
advice for parents?

00:41:03.795 --> 00:41:05.400
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Sure.

00:41:05.400 --> 00:41:05.980
Let's see.

00:41:05.980 --> 00:41:07.590
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:07.590 --> 00:41:08.420
A big question.

00:41:08.420 --> 00:41:08.880
DAVID LEVIN: Book two!

00:41:08.880 --> 00:41:10.380
SHAUNA TOMINEY: A big question.

00:41:10.380 --> 00:41:13.770
But I think parenting is hard.

00:41:13.770 --> 00:41:16.250
Parenting is hard work.

00:41:16.250 --> 00:41:19.050
I think there's a
lot of belief that's

00:41:19.050 --> 00:41:20.910
really prevalent
that you should just

00:41:20.910 --> 00:41:23.520
know what to do as a parent.

00:41:23.520 --> 00:41:27.600
And so when you seek out
support or parenting education,

00:41:27.600 --> 00:41:29.970
there's a lot of
stigma that's still

00:41:29.970 --> 00:41:33.780
pervasive in our society about
doing that, that that's only

00:41:33.780 --> 00:41:36.000
for bad parents, or those
parents who don't know what

00:41:36.000 --> 00:41:37.666
they're doing, rather
than acknowledging

00:41:37.666 --> 00:41:38.880
that this is learned.

00:41:38.880 --> 00:41:41.550
We are trying our
hardest along the way.

00:41:41.550 --> 00:41:44.500
And parenting is a challenge,
regardless of your background,

00:41:44.500 --> 00:41:46.960
regardless of your
education level.

00:41:46.960 --> 00:41:48.940
Parenting some
children is harder than

00:41:48.940 --> 00:41:51.800
others, depending on
your own personality,

00:41:51.800 --> 00:41:54.250
their personalities,
and their needs as well,

00:41:54.250 --> 00:41:56.170
and the context
that you live in.

00:41:56.170 --> 00:41:58.240
And so one of the
pieces of advice

00:41:58.240 --> 00:42:01.780
I have is to be more
compassionate to one another.

00:42:01.780 --> 00:42:04.040
So often, we're
fearful of being judged

00:42:04.040 --> 00:42:06.040
when we're standing in
line at the grocery store

00:42:06.040 --> 00:42:09.070
and our child is melting down,
or we're in the parking lot,

00:42:09.070 --> 00:42:11.290
just trying to get
in the car, and we're

00:42:11.290 --> 00:42:14.290
looking around hoping
that nobody else sees us.

00:42:14.290 --> 00:42:16.990
And so to think about, what
can we do in those moments

00:42:16.990 --> 00:42:21.040
to be a support for one another,
to see each other as learners,

00:42:21.040 --> 00:42:24.070
just as we're trying to help
our children see themselves,

00:42:24.070 --> 00:42:27.615
and to be there for one another.

00:42:27.615 --> 00:42:30.360
DAVID LEVIN: I guess my
last question, and maybe

00:42:30.360 --> 00:42:33.690
the last question if nobody else
comes up, but is there anything

00:42:33.690 --> 00:42:36.040
else you'd like readers
to know about your book,

00:42:36.040 --> 00:42:38.164
"Creating Compassionate
Kids," or in general,

00:42:38.164 --> 00:42:39.330
creating compassionate kids?

00:42:39.330 --> 00:42:40.500
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Sure.

00:42:40.500 --> 00:42:44.850
Oh gosh, let me think for a
moment in terms of anything

00:42:44.850 --> 00:42:48.310
that we haven't shared yet.

00:42:48.310 --> 00:42:54.700
I think that as we said,
it's never too late.

00:42:54.700 --> 00:42:56.250
Parenting is hard.

00:42:56.250 --> 00:42:59.220
And acknowledging that
the more you know,

00:42:59.220 --> 00:43:01.510
the more tools you have
in your parenting toolbox.

00:43:01.510 --> 00:43:03.800
And so I really just
appreciate you being here,

00:43:03.800 --> 00:43:06.430
appreciate you being
here to learn, to share.

00:43:06.430 --> 00:43:09.160
I'd be more than happy
to answer or chat

00:43:09.160 --> 00:43:11.517
about specific questions.

00:43:11.517 --> 00:43:13.600
DAVID LEVIN: And I don't
get in the last question.

00:43:13.600 --> 00:43:15.956
SHAUNA TOMINEY:
Sure, absolutely.

00:43:15.956 --> 00:43:20.800
AUDIENCE: So I'm probably
going to have white kids.

00:43:20.800 --> 00:43:24.550
You talked about
in some situations,

00:43:24.550 --> 00:43:27.790
it's more important to--

00:43:27.790 --> 00:43:30.580
some families, you end up having
more conversations about what

00:43:30.580 --> 00:43:32.290
life is like growing
up, how people

00:43:32.290 --> 00:43:34.210
are going to perceive you based
on the color of your skin,

00:43:34.210 --> 00:43:36.160
knowing maybe you're going to
have more death in your family

00:43:36.160 --> 00:43:37.850
because you're a-- your thing.

00:43:40.660 --> 00:43:43.900
What are your recommendations
for having those conversations

00:43:43.900 --> 00:43:47.350
from a more privileged
standpoint without instilling

00:43:47.350 --> 00:43:50.140
a sense of intrinsic guilt
for having that privilege?

00:43:50.140 --> 00:43:51.280
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Yeah.

00:43:51.280 --> 00:43:52.510
That is a great question.

00:43:52.510 --> 00:43:55.040
And I have a whole section of
the book on, as I mentioned,

00:43:55.040 --> 00:43:55.840
self-awareness.

00:43:55.840 --> 00:43:57.820
And I think that one
of the things that we

00:43:57.820 --> 00:44:00.850
can do for our children is not
just talk about the qualities

00:44:00.850 --> 00:44:03.050
that make them who they are.

00:44:03.050 --> 00:44:05.590
My daughter is also
very fair-skinned.

00:44:05.590 --> 00:44:08.860
She has blue eyes, despite the
other dark eyes in our family.

00:44:08.860 --> 00:44:10.720
And she will, in our
country, probably

00:44:10.720 --> 00:44:12.580
never be discriminated
against because

00:44:12.580 --> 00:44:14.680
of the color of her skin.

00:44:14.680 --> 00:44:18.700
And so thinking about how do
we, with children of all races,

00:44:18.700 --> 00:44:20.650
talk about race?

00:44:20.650 --> 00:44:25.480
And with honesty, in
terms of how challenging

00:44:25.480 --> 00:44:27.890
and how race is
seen in our society.

00:44:27.890 --> 00:44:30.310
So often, we want
to teach children

00:44:30.310 --> 00:44:33.290
that differences don't matter.

00:44:33.290 --> 00:44:34.960
But the truth is they do.

00:44:34.960 --> 00:44:41.150
There are some children growing
up recognizing and living

00:44:41.150 --> 00:44:43.610
the fact that their differences
do matter in the way

00:44:43.610 --> 00:44:46.700
that people look at them,
treat them, the opportunities

00:44:46.700 --> 00:44:47.860
that they have.

00:44:47.860 --> 00:44:50.090
And I think that if
we have conversations

00:44:50.090 --> 00:44:52.470
with all of our
children about race,

00:44:52.470 --> 00:44:57.110
about sexual orientation,
about gender identity,

00:44:57.110 --> 00:44:59.900
about different cultures,
different religions,

00:44:59.900 --> 00:45:03.170
we can help our children
think about the impact of that

00:45:03.170 --> 00:45:05.360
in their own life,
and help them feel

00:45:05.360 --> 00:45:08.540
comfortable emerging into
who they're growing up to be.

00:45:08.540 --> 00:45:11.480
But also help them to
see both the challenges

00:45:11.480 --> 00:45:13.310
and the strengths that
other people have.

00:45:13.310 --> 00:45:16.580
Because we really want them
to see that as a strength,

00:45:16.580 --> 00:45:18.450
and that diversity
as a strength,

00:45:18.450 --> 00:45:22.470
rather than a difference
to be afraid of.

00:45:22.470 --> 00:45:24.654
DAVID LEVIN: And last question.

00:45:24.654 --> 00:45:25.570
AUDIENCE: No pressure.

00:45:25.570 --> 00:45:26.860
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Sure.

00:45:26.860 --> 00:45:31.670
AUDIENCE: So we're not
originally from the US.

00:45:31.670 --> 00:45:34.400
I'm from Israel, so
we're Jewish, turns out.

00:45:34.400 --> 00:45:36.590
And we walk around
with our kids,

00:45:36.590 --> 00:45:38.540
and there's these--
you pose with Santa

00:45:38.540 --> 00:45:39.620
and all these things.

00:45:39.620 --> 00:45:41.410
And you know, my daughter says,
hey, let's stand this line.

00:45:41.410 --> 00:45:42.870
And I explain to
her, no, it's OK,

00:45:42.870 --> 00:45:43.820
we don't stand in
this line, because we

00:45:43.820 --> 00:45:45.110
don't celebrate Christmas.

00:45:45.110 --> 00:45:45.609
Why?

00:45:45.609 --> 00:45:47.630
Because do Hanukkah, whatever.

00:45:47.630 --> 00:45:50.210
The problem happens when
she goes back to school.

00:45:50.210 --> 00:45:52.910
And we don't send her
to a Jewish school,

00:45:52.910 --> 00:45:57.030
because we feel she
should be with everyone.

00:45:57.030 --> 00:45:59.030
Basically, so one of her
friends says something,

00:45:59.030 --> 00:46:02.802
like hey, I got picture with
Santa, and my daughter goes,

00:46:02.802 --> 00:46:04.010
we don't celebrate Christmas.

00:46:04.010 --> 00:46:04.610
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:04.610 --> 00:46:07.091
And my instinct is to
try to explain to her,

00:46:07.091 --> 00:46:08.090
that's not what you say.

00:46:08.090 --> 00:46:09.980
I mean, it's OK for
other people to have--

00:46:09.980 --> 00:46:12.440
how do I get around
that while on one hand,

00:46:12.440 --> 00:46:14.636
trying to maintain our--

00:46:14.636 --> 00:46:16.260
I don't know if its
values or beliefs--

00:46:16.260 --> 00:46:18.920
but on the other hand, still
making sure that she respects

00:46:18.920 --> 00:46:20.540
everyone else's?

00:46:20.540 --> 00:46:22.730
Because she's not
getting a bad example,

00:46:22.730 --> 00:46:24.360
but she's perceiving
it that way.

00:46:24.360 --> 00:46:24.860
Sorry.

00:46:24.860 --> 00:46:25.735
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Yeah.

00:46:25.735 --> 00:46:27.530
No, no, it's a great question.

00:46:27.530 --> 00:46:31.525
One, all of the other parents
in the classroom, in my opinion,

00:46:31.525 --> 00:46:32.900
should be thinking
about how they

00:46:32.900 --> 00:46:36.320
talk to their children
about other cultures,

00:46:36.320 --> 00:46:39.380
about people celebrating
in other ways,

00:46:39.380 --> 00:46:42.260
having other holidays,
other religions.

00:46:42.260 --> 00:46:44.220
Because then, when
another child says,

00:46:44.220 --> 00:46:47.600
oh, you don't
celebrate Christmas?

00:46:47.600 --> 00:46:49.279
What do you celebrate instead?

00:46:49.279 --> 00:46:51.320
And seeing that as something
to be interested in,

00:46:51.320 --> 00:46:53.810
and wanting to learn about,
and seeing that as part of--

00:46:53.810 --> 00:46:56.240
in our community, we
all have different ways

00:46:56.240 --> 00:47:00.170
of thinking about things, of
sharing, of coming together

00:47:00.170 --> 00:47:02.310
in our family, with our culture.

00:47:02.310 --> 00:47:05.810
And so one piece of that
question, which you don't have

00:47:05.810 --> 00:47:07.070
control over.

00:47:07.070 --> 00:47:08.750
And then the other
in terms of the way

00:47:08.750 --> 00:47:11.450
that you approach
your daughter--

00:47:11.450 --> 00:47:12.410
it's OK.

00:47:12.410 --> 00:47:15.620
And it's OK for her to say,
we don't celebrate Christmas,

00:47:15.620 --> 00:47:17.570
here's what we
celebrate instead.

00:47:17.570 --> 00:47:19.460
Or here's what's
important in my family.

00:47:19.460 --> 00:47:21.890
And I think too
often, it's folks

00:47:21.890 --> 00:47:25.370
who, in your case, in
the community that you're

00:47:25.370 --> 00:47:28.490
living in, come from
the minority group--

00:47:28.490 --> 00:47:30.050
too often, it falls
on your shoulders

00:47:30.050 --> 00:47:33.290
to be the one to explain,
to educate, or even

00:47:33.290 --> 00:47:37.250
defend your family
to others because

00:47:37.250 --> 00:47:38.900
of that lack of
awareness, or the lack

00:47:38.900 --> 00:47:40.180
of those conversations.

00:47:40.180 --> 00:47:41.930
And that's one of the
things that I really

00:47:41.930 --> 00:47:44.210
am striving to help change.

00:47:44.210 --> 00:47:47.310
But I think what you're
doing with your daughter--

00:47:47.310 --> 00:47:49.070
it's a challenge,
in terms of thinking

00:47:49.070 --> 00:47:53.690
about how do we help her then be
that role model of recognizing

00:47:53.690 --> 00:47:56.180
where our family fits
in to this other more

00:47:56.180 --> 00:47:58.147
dominant society around them.

00:47:58.147 --> 00:47:58.980
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:47:58.980 --> 00:48:00.580
SHAUNA TOMINEY: Thank
you for bringing that up.

00:48:00.580 --> 00:48:02.900
DAVID LEVIN: Thank you very
much for coming and talking

00:48:02.900 --> 00:48:04.274
about your book,
and ways that we

00:48:04.274 --> 00:48:05.964
can create compassionate kids.

00:48:05.964 --> 00:48:07.380
SHAUNA TOMINEY:
Thank you so much.

00:48:07.380 --> 00:48:09.090
I really appreciate
you taking the time.

00:48:09.090 --> 00:48:13.040
